TripReport: This was part of a circumambulation of Chenrezig, walking from Yading Village at a starting elevation of around 3988 m and then around Chenrezig and back to Yading Village. The entire route was about 25 km with 1255 m of gain, with two major mountain pass high points, including one at about Songduoyakou that was the high point with an elevation of 4688 m. Our guides set up tents for us slightly over midway through the route to spend one night. We encountered a mix of mild sleet and blue skies, as well as quite a few blue sheep. The trail was well-maintained with part of it being a boardwalk and the rest being a mostly dirt path with some small scree.

I took three nights to trek this route, but that last night was really just to relax, so this could be readily done with just two nights. I spent the night in Cachora and then got a ride up to the building at Camping Choquequirao Wasi, where I met up with a guide who had a donkey that would carry my backpacking pack most of the time. As this was my first major trek, I followed advice to do this, and I'm glad for the time I had chatting with the guide, but I also know that one could do this while carrying their own pack without too much difficulty. The side of the Apurimac Canyon you descend down after passing Capuliyoc is very dry with large yucca plants. You get down to a bridge at the bottom to go over the Apurimac River, and once on the other side, it's much more of a cloud rainforest with lusher vegetation and more insects. I camped the first night in my tent on a terrace at Marampata, which had a great view looking out into the canyon. The next day I explored Choquequirao all day with maybe 15-20 other people being there at the same time. I returned to the same camping spot in the afternoon and went most of the way back the next day, camping at the Cocamansana site despite being there pretty early in the day. The final day was very short getting back to the trailhead.
Started early and high tailed it up here. I was the first one up for at least 10 minutes. It s an amazing view.
Passed up and over this spot on the way to see the 2017 eclipse. Amazing view from the top, and it s a pretty easy hike in besides the altitude.
Watched the 2017 total solar eclipse from up here. It was a truly amazing experience.
I camped inside the crater here and went to the summit to watch the sunset. It was very windy but peaceful.
Very desolate with lots of red rocks up here. Smoky but satisfying.

Our team of four started close to midnight from the trailhead after a short sleep at a camp nearby. We were the first to ascend and did so within an hour after sunrise at about 7:40. We were the only ones up there for about an hour, and it was lucky in that when we came down around 9 AM, few people were trying to come up. It only took me two minutes to go down the ropes since I just ran down, opening and closing my gloved hands on the wire to move past the connectors. When we finally returned to Vernal Falls, it was so packed full of people that we lost each other in the crowd.

PeakPointName: Four Corners Monument AZ-CO-NM-UT Quad Point

TripReport: Started from Thorung Pedi around 6-7 AM and summited around 9 AM. I hiked up the slope to the right just enough to reach 5420m. I had no issues with altitude sickness, but the long walk down to Muktinath was pretty tough on my knees, and I slipped on some ice a couple times. Felt great to get in to Muktinath and celebrate with all those people who I d been seeing repeatedly on the way up.

Great view from the top. A nice walk up, but my friend and I brought mountain bikes to the top to ride down, and the trail we took down had lots of blowdowns requiring you to stop, toss the bike over, and climb over the fallen trees.

Summited this on the way up to Indrahar Pass. I brought a tent up to sleep near the  Dhauladhar Cafe , and made my way atop the pass the next morning. The climb was very steep and icy, and it was pretty sketchy to do with just normal hiking boots. I saw some people at the top of the pass, and they showed me an easier way down, but it was still very icy.

I rented a tent and camped by the 'Dhauladhar Cafe', where I bought some much appreciated maggi, and then started early in the morning solo to get to the top. I had just normal hiking boots on with no traction, and the ice made much of the ascent very slippery. However, I realized later that I had deviated from the expected route somewhat, which led me onto steeper and icier rock. The route finding was tough with all the snow lightly covering the rocks. Luckily the views at the summit were as clear as they could be, and they were truly incredible. Another group joined me at the summit, and I followed them back down on the standard path. I would recommend microspikes to make the ascent easier if doing it in November. This route is probably pretty straightforward when the ice has melted.

I rented a motorbike and mask from my homestay and came up here solo in the evening. It was fascinating seeing the miners working at night and the sulfur dripping out of the rock, though I could only dimly make out the blue flames through the gas.

After taking a 1-2 hour mototaxi up to the trailhead, I proceeded to hike and up to the crater rim without too much effort. One thing I did differently from the others there was to circle around the whole rim. There s another much greener volcanic crater on the other side of the crater from where the ascent trail is! It s definitely worth going to the other side of the crater to see this.

Fascinating place with all sorts of ancient tree and plant species, including many covered in spikes. You ll want to cover your skin on this hike since there s so many sharp plants to poke you. It started raining on my climb, which brought out some animal life. I spotted a frilled neck lizard running on its hind legs across a puddle on the trail, and a snake that I believe was the extremely venomous coastal taipan ran across the trail right in front of me, nearly touching the front of my shoes. The steepest, muddiest sections of the hike have fixed ropes to help you get up and down. This hike was a highlight of my Queensland trip.
I went up in the dark to summit around 7:15 AM. This is an easy walk up.

I left by 4 or 5 AM from the Routeburn Flats Hut and had the Routeburn Track all to myself for several hours. It was amazing watching the sun rise and illuminate the Southern Alps.

Latitude: -44.726796, Longitude: 168.170379
It was a nice walk up if a little steep at times. It s basically walking up a steep grass slope. The views were stunning up there.

I took my cousin with me to climb Mount Saint Helens starting around 3-4 AM. It was already foggy at the start, which made following the clearly marked poles up the summer route difficult. It proceeded to rain after sunrise, but we didn t give up, making it to the crater rim around 8:45 AM with 30+ mph winds and a max of like 100 feet of visibility. We didn t encounter snow on the trail, but there were some patches not far away. I didn t know at the time there was a higher summit, and there was no way to see it in those conditions. We slowly down scrambled the rocky sections and tried to dry off out completely soaked clothes by getting a meal at the Lone Fir Cafe in Cougar.

Accidentally went across the ridge from the summit of Martin to Cheops in a day trip that was supposed to bag Martin and Switchback. It was an exposed scramble traverse from Martin to get to Cheops, and there was some steep walking down to get back to the Martin Creek Trail. Had to go back to get Switchback a while later.

Went on a day trip to bag Martin and Switchback, but ended up going the wrong way on the ridge to Cheops instead. It s a bit of a scramble to get up Martin, but nothing too bad. There s a decent amount of larches to see from the top too.

Practiced winter camping and built an igloo nearby, and then snowshoed up to the top of Beljica. Great time with great people. We needed proper trucks to move over the snowy roads and get closer to the trailhead.
Easy snowshoe to the top and a great name.

It s a long snowshoe up the forest before you get any views, but the views at the top were incredible. I summited later in the afternoon and saw rollerballs across the snowshoe tracks where people were coming up from the treeline to the summit, so watch out for avy hazards in the last part of the ascent.

I camped with a group at around 8k feet just for the experience, but it was bitter cold at maybe -17F in the night. We got up around 2 AM and summited around 7:45 AM, about an hour after sunrise. The wind chill was around -13F at the summit, and all our water froze solid, even the Nalgenes. The ice coming up the Pearly Gates was blue and very difficult to drive an axe into, and so to descend we went down the soft snow on the Old Chute and then cut back across to the Hogsback. A benefit of this early season climb was very little rock fall and no bergschrund. Dehydrated from our water being frozen, it took a while to get back to the trailhead, about 11h total from camp to summit to trailhead.

We camped on the snow over the frozen Colchuck Lake after snowshoeing in. In the early morning, we ascended part of the way up the couloir between Dragontail and Colchuck Peak in snowshoes and then switched to crampons when the snow was firm enough. After reaching the col, we turned right and traversed around the side of Colchuck Peak not facing the lake, summiting around 8 AM. The snow was thin enough that my crampons would occasionally catch rock underneath and stop suddenly, which had me trip a couple times. It was incredible to see the Stuart Range covered in snow and ice from the summit. There was a very long glissade back down the couloir, and then we snowshoed out to the trailhead. We could hear avalanches happening somewhere behind us in the afternoon well after we had reached the forest below Colchuck Lake. The snow added about 8 miles roundtrip of road walking.
I prefer this winter route up Ellinor compared to the summer one. It s a straightforward snow climb up and a fun glissade back down.

This is ended up being a legendary climb among our group of mountaineering friends. It started with crossing the slumped over bridge and then going up the steepest forest ascent I ve ever seen, which basically involved pulling yourself up fallen tree trunks. Then began a long snowshoe made longer by our accidental decision to go up and over a hill when we could have stayed in the valley, necessitating a very steep snowshoe descent back to the trail. We set up camp on the frozen lake south of the peak, and the next morning was a very enjoyable snow climb to the summit, which we reached around 8 AM.  We decided to descend by scrambling down some exposed rocks and then snow back to camp. One of our team members had a foot injury that made the snowshoe out very difficult, and it was getting late by the time we reached the forest descent again, which had us climbing down trees like ladders. The beauty of the snowy peaks and the remoteness of this place made it one of my favorites.

Once you pass Lena Lake, there s a difficult log river crossing and lots of blowdowns to navigate over like walking so many balance beams. We camped beyond a series of thick blowdowns and summited the next day around 8 AM. Much of the ascent was over bare rock, but there was steep, solid snow in the steep couloir closer to the summit. I went up it with an axe and crampons to be safe, but some of my partners just used their bare mountaineering boots. A baby goat came up to us on the way up. Incredible views from the top. It was a long way back over those blowdowns with a full pack, and the river was very high and fast when crossing the logs back to the Lena Lake trail.

Camped the night before most of the way up with two friends. It was great to start with sea lion barks in the distance and pass through different ecological zones with changes in vegetation before reaching the top. Great way to see Big Sur.

I summited Baker with a large group via the Easton route. A small group of us ended up crossing the river too far down on the way up and got stuck with a group of others on a silty slope trying to get up to the railroad grade, so other team members had to lower hand lines to us so we could pull ourselves up. We camped on the Easton Glacier and practiced some crevasse rescue skills while up there. We got an alpine start the next morning and summited without too much issue, though I found myself much more fatigued than expected. There were huge crevasses out, but we largely avoided them. The proper river crossing was much more obvious on the way back down. Shout out to the trip organizers for making everything happen.

I summited Adams in beautiful weather with two friends. It was a really nice ascent after spending the night at the Lunch Counter given the firmness of the snow, and we were among the first at the summit around 6:15 AM. A small plane flew close by for a look too. Unfortunately, things were still icy on the way down, so glissading was too sketchy and we had to walk down the whole way.
Run from Wallingford up Interlaken Park up the Volunteer Park water tower and then down through the arboretum.
Hiked from the visitor s center over Johnston Ridge to Harry s Ridge. There were great crater views, and we spotted a herd of elk.
Spotted a herd of elk on this hike from the visitor s center over Johnston Ridge and to Harry s Ridge. Great views of the crater the whole way.
Went to Steamboat Prow as training for the Emmons route. Practiced crevasse rescue and glissaded on the Inter Glacier.

This was an attempt at the Emmons route on a four-person rope team. We went up just above Camp Schurman and set up camp the first day. We started up very early the next morning and made it up to just about 12k feet when the extremely hard and remarkably frictionless ice combined with the 35 mph winds convinced us to abandon the attempt and turn around. Seeing the sun rise over our descent off the Emmons was a special treat, though. Those trying to summit in July should be wary of how solid and smooth the ice can be on the Emmons.

Somehow the first day of us getting to camp wasn t saved on my GPS track, so the stats you see are just for the second and third days. We took one day to head to a camp well past White Pass that was directly west of Point 7829 and off of a creek and small tarn freed by the melting snow. The views at this camp were stunning, but unfortunately the small pool of water made a couple of our party members sick by later the next day. We got an early start the next day and roped up to cross the Suiattle Glacier, though at this time there were only very small crevasses, and we saw solo and unroped climbers on the trail too. The final ascent was just an easy walk up on a bare, dusty trail, and the wind and weather were so perfect at the summit that there were butterflies flying all around there. It was a long approach back to camp for one more night of rest and watching a spectacular sunset. We saw some deer by White Pass the next day as we left camp, and it was a very long walk back down to the car. Overall, this was my favorite volcano ascent since it was so varied and beautiful.

A couple friends and I got a permit to camp at the summit of Ruby, which had amazing views of the North Cascades, especially at sunset and sunrise. It was a long walk up from the Colonial Creek trailhead, and the only tough section was a steep walk up a mostly solid slope with some scree at the very end. I fully recommend this if you get the opportunity.

This was a relatively late season ascent of the Disappointment Cleaver route. Went up and camped at Ingraham Flats the first day, and then summited the next day around 9:30 AM. There was only one ladder crossing, a double ladder leaned diagonally across a huge crevasse that we hit around 6 AM. It was nice and sunny, but that did mean that when we got back past the Bowling Alley there was a decent bit of rock fall. We really took our time on the descent, eventually even taking a brief wrong turn towards Panorama Point on the way back down in the dark. It was very late in the evening by the time we drove out of there. Great time with a great team!

Climbed up this little rock while on the Ozette Triangle Loop. I camped at a site nearby, and at this point in the season, 3-4 bears were coming down the beach to look for fish before hibernation. Though I did see a couple day hikers in the morning, by the late afternoon there was no one else nearby. At dusk as I cooked food, a bear came down the trail towards me. I was able to scare it away once it got within 40ish feet, and it went off the beach up into the forest, after which I didn t see it again. I woke up the next day to a family of deer nearby and saw raccoons by the trail as I walked the rest of the way. Fall is a great time to be out here since there are so many animals out and few people.
See peakbagger.com

The first day we got to glissade down from Longs Pass and took our camping gear all the way up the Cascadian Couloir to camp at the top around 7450 ft for some extra views. We then took a very exciting snow and rock scramble traverse across to the west before ascending again to meet the ridge and get the summit around 10:30. We got some very steep glissading in after traversing back east mostly on rock and packed up camp. The descent was brutal on our knees with those full packs, and some of the steps going down the couloir were so big that I had to hang by my hands and drop down. The sun was setting by the time we made it back up and over Longs Pass, and it was almost dark by the time we reached the trailhead. It was an exhausting experience to bring camping supplies so far up the route, but it was a lot of fun too.

We hit this false summit as part of an unsuccessful 3-day attempt at summiting Olympus. We camped at Elk Lake, started maybe not as early as we should have the next day to head towards the moraine, wasting maybe an hour accidentally trying to go down the terminal moraine primitive trail instead of to the side of the moraine. We descended onto the Blue Glacier and roped up, but by then it was very hot down there, like 90+ degrees. We made our way up the mountain to the false summit, but by then we had already met another party coming down who were saying that the snow was too unstable to safely reach the summit block. We saw for ourselves that there was a large bergschrund separating us from the summit block, and the snow was too soft to protect trying to get on there. We decided to give up and turn back, and by the time we started descending the snow, it was warm and slushy enough that we set up a snow anchor and the leader of our rope team belayed us down the first portion of the descent. Again it was intolerably hot on the glacier surface, and we made it back to camp to spend one more night before heading out. Highlights included seeing Olympus up close and passing a herd of elk near the Hoh River. Ultimately, it was a beautiful, remarkable trip, but we did fail to grab the exact summit. As far as I know, every party failed to summit that day except for a group of two people who split off of our larger party, camped by the summit block until everything froze over at night, and then summited in the dark.
We passed this on the way to an attempt at the Olympus summit that was ultimately unsuccessful. See peakbagger.com
This was a two night trip. It was blistering hot at the trailhead and was a simple walk up despite how long it was. The last summit push involves some long talus fields.

Got up early and did the Pearly Gates in the dark to watch the sunrise from the summit with only a couple other groups up there. That was all well and easy, but the descent was awful since so many parties came up after us, and we had to squeeze past them to descend the Pearly Gates. There were so many people that at one time while I was down climbing, I looked up and saw three pairs of boots and crampons right by my face. I recommend the sunrise summit and then trying to get down ASAP before the sun fully rises and the crowds arrive or take the Old Chute down.

It was a steep snow ascent up through the forest and some icy steps over rock before we got to this summit. We had planned on grabbing Middle Chiwaukum too, but it was fogged over and windy at the top and looked like it was only going to get worse over on that summit. Of course things started to clear as we came down.
There was a bit of snow to walk over on the top, but otherwise it was an easy, straightforward walk up to the summit with great views over Lake Cushman and out to Mount Rainier.
Took some electric bikes up. It was quite the workout, and it was so much fun flying down the road on the descent!

There s an easy switchback trail to the lookout, and from there it s a somewhat exposed scramble along a ridge to get to the actual summit, where there s an obvious USGS benchmark demarcating the right spot.

This is one of the best bang for your buck hikes in Washington. Easy switchbacks up to the overlook with great views over the North Cascades mountains. It s also worth the exposed but short and relatively easy scramble to get to the actual summit of Sauk Mountain, where you ll find a USGS benchmark.
A quick day trip to scramble Pinnacle and Plummer. It s not too difficult, but there is a good bit of loose scree to deal with. Great views of Rainier.
Summited with Pinnacle. See peakbagger.com
Went up at night to see the Perseid meteor shower. Lots of others had the same idea. It was wonderful to just lie back up on the ledge and watch the stars.

I accidentally went to Cheops from Martin instead of Switchback years before, so I had to get redemption with the same crew. This was a leisurely walk up and is probably the easiest Bulger in the Sawtooths. Anyone heading this way should try to link Switchback with Martin at least. It s a long walk just to summit the one peak.
Part of a loop also bagging Old Snowy. See peakbagger.com

We did a loop bagging Hawkeye Point and going down to Goat Lake the first day, camping that night around 46.50982, -121.47521. The next day we got up early and bagged Old Snowy Mountain. It was mostly a big rock pile with a clear trail, but there was some light scrambling at the very end and at least one spot where we walked over some snow. We rejoined the Snowgrass Trail and walked out from there. Amazing views of Mt St Helens, Adams, and Rainier.
Pretty good larches this time of year, and some great snowy mountain views. This is a long hike, but the trail is really easy.

This was a magical place to see the larches. Probably the thickest and most abundant place I ve ever seen them is up this trail in the meadow before the last steeper part to the summit. It s all an easy walk up, and from the top you can see sporadic larches on the sides of the tall mountain ridges around you.

This was a steep walk up mostly on a trail to reach the summit. At this time of the year, there was a short portion that was a climb up steep snow, and there was a set of slippery rocks with a fixed cable that made it much easier to get up and over. It was overcast and a little drizzly, but the views of Odda below and Folgefonna across the valley were fantastic.
Just a short walk from the funicular. Great views and a pleasant walk down into the city.

This was a fairly early season summit, and so I was the only one out there once I passed Munkebu. I started around 4 PM 6/18 from Sørvågen, reaching the cabin at Munkebu by about 7 PM. I had some difficulty getting up muddy sections on the way up with a full pack, but there are frequent sections where fixed chains are provided to help with the ascent. I turned west and picked a stunning campsite by 8 PM on the small elevated isthmus between Tennesvatnet and Fjerdallsvatnet with a gorgeous lookout south towards the latter and a view of Hermannsdalstinden itself. I got going around 6-7 AM the next day and summited around 10:40. Fog rolled in when I approached the summit and unfortunately didn t dissipate until around an hour after I was at the top. The approach up the ridge involved some fairly steep and exposed sections, and there were some patches of solid snow towards the top. I used my mountaineering boots, crampons, and an axe to ascend the snow for a quicker way up than scrambling the rocks the whole way, but there was an exposed rock scramble at the very top. The descent was pretty relaxing once I was past the steeper sections, but I did slip with the full pack a couple times coming down some of the chain sections most of the way back to the trailhead. I was back at the trailhead by 7-8 PM. This summit was one of the most scenic I have ever seen. It s truly amazing out on the Lofoten Islands.
This is a nice and easy walk up with part of the trail on raised wooden planks. There s a great view at the top over Kvalvika Beach.

This was such a fun scramble. It immediately shoots up in a steep forest ascent that turns into a rock scramble after a break in a meadow. I did it all in fog, so I couldn t get a sense of the real exposure. Descending back through the forest was steep and slippery enough to have me fall on my butt a few times.

This was a fun trip up Mt St Helens. There was an enthusiastic volunteer sharing facts about the mountain with everyone up at the crater rim. We continued on the to the true summit, and though the trail got steep at times, the snow that remained was firm and was easy to not slip on. Went up in three season mountaineering boots and didn t really need any traction since most of the trail was bare rock. You ll see from the GPS track that we deviated from the typical path on the way down. This was because we were able to glissade nearly half way down by going down a gully to the west of the main trail instead of walking down. Then we just traversed back over to the trail. That saved a bunch of time, and it was quality glissading.

Beautiful fluffy white wildflowers were all around on this hike. A short section near the top involved walking over some snow, but microspikes were not necessary. Waterproof boots were useful with all the wet sections of the trail. There are fantastic views of Rainier up at the summit, as well as a cool fire lookout hut.

I went with a partner to camp in the Wolf Creek Basin. There were several blowdowns covered in ash, so my hands, pants, and shirt got coated in ash going up and over those trees. There was a herd of deer that came through to inspect our camp, and they stuck around as we made our ascent in the early morning. The route finding was mostly straightforward walking straight up the ridge to Gardner. The scramble across the ridgeline to North Gardner felt Class 3 at most with solid handholds.
Part of a trip to bag this and North Gardner. See peakbagger.com
Amazing views and a long but very well maintained trail.

Our team of three made the traverse across the side of the valley above Fisher Creek and set up camp around 48.57267, -120.87821 in the morning. Easy Pass was as the name suggests, but that traverse was pretty steep with some interesting moves over scree, all with a bit of runoff down the slope before lots of exposure. After setting up camp, we scrambled up Mesahchie first and then traversed over to Katsuk, later descending as the sun set to camp the night and leave the next morning. The rock was very loose until you reach the top sections of the climb, and there s a lot of  kitty litter  rocks strewn over the lower hand and foot holds. It all makes for a scenic and exciting scramble, but also one in which you have to be sure of your holds.
This was part of a trip to also summit Mesahchie. See peakbagger.com

I grabbed a taxi from Litochoro to start the climb at 5:30 AM. It only took a little over 4h to reach the summit from there, after which I had a relaxing descent chatting and grabbing soup from the Spilios Agapitos refuge. The scrambling was a bit icy at times, but it was mostly very straightforward and not sketchy. The rock was solid, and there were times where good holds were marked with spray paint. It is exposed, so this could be difficult for those not comfortable with heights.
I only recorded the ascent, so double the stats for the full hike.

Hiked up to camp at the  Horse Camp  area by Upper Eagle Lake with three other people. We decided to split up, with two going the long walk up way around to the summit and me and a friend going straight up the scramble to the top. The direct route mostly involved a straightforward walk up on scree, and then there s a short section of actually scrambling up a chimney to the summit. After waiting  a while for the other party to get there we all took the easy long way back down to the trail. There were definitely some larches out here, but they were more sporadic than I had seen in top larch viewing spots like Carne Mountain or in the Enchantments.
A pretty straightforward snowshoe besides some icy direct lines we took to get up on the ridges.

This was a winter trip up Mt St Helens with a great group of people. We camped at the trailhead in surprisingly comfortable temperatures, but our sleep was interrupted several times by snowmobiles repeatedly revving their engines in the middle of the night. We were started around 2:45 AM and took a moderate pace up, getting to the crater rim around 10:40. It was a bluebird sky day, but it was also freezing cold. Given that some of us had gotten the true summit before and the others didn t seem that interested in heading over to it, we just relaxed below the crater rim to block the wind and then started back down. We tried to glissade as much as possible, but for the most part the ground wasn t steep enough and the snow was too soft. We celebrated with pizza at the Lone Fir Cafe in Cougar afterwards. The total time was about 14 hours.
Trail ran to the top in a loop from Murray and Liverpool up Forest, north across the summit and to Mount Stuart Lookout, and back down via Mount Stuart Rd, Mellifont, Arthur, and finally Murray.
Bagged Tyler and Baldy together in an easy walk up.
Summited with Tyler Peak. See the GPS track at peakbagger.com
Part of a loop bagging Earl, Bean, Devil s Head, and Volcanic Neck. See peakbagger.com
Part of a loop bagging Earl, Bean, Devil s Head, and Volcanic Neck. See peakbagger.com

A foggy, rainy trip into the Teanaways. Started out coming up Bean Creek and made the first ascent up Earl Peak, which was pretty easy and hardly a scramble. The traverse over to Bean took a bit of time, but was otherwise straightforward. I rushed north to grab Devil s Head, which was a relatively easy scramble, and then I grabbed Volcanic Neck on the way back, which had the most interesting and exposed scrambling but only really took 45 minutes to go up and down. It was tricky in the fog to find the right way to get down Bean to start down the unmaintained trail marked on the map, so getting back off the summit of Bean was probably the sketchiest down climbing of the whole trip until I found the trail down.
Part of a loop bagging Earl, Bean, Devil s Head, and Volcanic Neck. See peakbagger.com
Great bang for your buck. Good views, easy trail, and very fast to complete.

After finding out that the West Fork Methow River Trail had a bridge out, I foolishly tried to go for Azurite from the Brown Bear TH. I went down, set up a camp just past Glacier Pass, and kept going, starting the bushwhack ascent from the PCT at about 2 PM. It was very slow going shoving my way through the brush up the hill. It seemed like thunderclouds were forming, and I had only made out up 1000 ft into the bushwhack with another 3k feet to go to the summit and a long ascent back to my camp. The only other guy out there who summited told me how sketchy the scree descent was, so with all that info and especially the threat of thunderstorms, I decided to give up and head back to camp. The next day I grabbed Tatie just to have summited something. It was a long couple days, but the views out there were incredible.

Pretty much just a walk up, with some cross grassy meadow travel where the ground can be a little squishy and wet. Towards the end there s a minor scramble around the left as you approach the summit block.

It was a beautiful, long day bagging Sahale and Boston. Our team of three passed by a family of mountain goats on Sahale Arm around 8 AM and crossed the Sahale Glacier by 10 AM, summiting Sahale around 11 AM. It was a relatively straightforward scramble across the ridgeline towards Boston until we dropped to the right. At that point hand and footholds were much less stable. However, once we reached the summit block of Boston, it was a relatively quick and easy scramble to the top, which we reached by 2:45 PM. Our team leader helped out another team to ascend and then descend safely for the next three or so hours. We  rappelled three pitches and then followed them as they made the traverse back across to Sahale. We decided to rappel one pitch off of Sahale to save time, and we finally got back across the glacier not long after sunset. It must have been around midnight when we got back to the car, and then it was a long drive back to Seattle.
Summited on the way to Boston Peak. See peakbagger.com

Went up the Sulphide Glacier route in a long day trip with two teams. We attempted the 5.2 variation going up the ridge to the east of the main route, but it was too difficult for our party. This detour ate up a few hours. We backtracked to the main scramble route, which was very easy and took maybe 30 minutes to reach the summit from where the scrambling began. Rappelling was relatively straightforward with multiple easy to spot anchors set up. It was dark by the time we got off the glacier and late in the evening when we returned to the trailhead. With the extra time trying to protect and climb the ridge, the whole trip ended up being around 24 hours.

I started in the early morning directly from Dongpu Hostel, passing by some water deer in the dark. It took about 5.5h to summit, after which I took my time taking pictures and chatting with people on the way down. It s almost entirely an easy walk up, and the short scrambly bits at the summit have bolted in chains to make going up very easy. There are several interesting temples to see on the way. I was picked up at the trailhead instead of walking the extra little bit back to the hostel. Make sure to get all the necessary permits, as that s definitely the toughest part.
So nice I did it twice. This is such a great place to see larches, it s definitely worth coming back to multiple times.
Part of a Si -> Tenerife loop trip. See peakbagger.com
Made the short scramble up the Haystack as part of a trip connecting over to Tenerife in a big loop.
Part of a Si -> Tenerife loop trip. See peakbagger.com
Camped up here to see the aurora. It wasn t as spectacular as the previous night, but I could see the green glow and some distinct bands looking north into Canada in the early evening.

I started from the Camp Senia trail and encountered snow by about 9k feet. Despite bringing snowshoes, the snow was a thin crust that had me punching through at times up to my waist every few steps. I made it up to a hill at just over 9600 feet so I could see into the Beartooths a bit and turned around from there after deciding the slog wasn t worth it. I got 7.85 miles in 5.5h, which shows how much the postholing was impacting speed. I think with thicker snow or no snow at all this would been really straightforward walk up, but June is a tricky month for snow quality.
Very easy trail, and there seemed to be lots of families summiting this state high point. Saw a baby goat at the top.
Thought I d do a little trail run here, but a lot of this is overgrown, so it was more like walking fast and pushing past poison ivy and other leafy plants. Nearly ran over a fawn.
Very easy trail that is well-marked.

I did a loop bagging the Catskill 3500 peaks Table Mountain, Peekamoose, Lone Mountain, Rocky Mountain, Balsam Cap, and Friday Mountain. The time listed here should be about 11-12h moving since I forgot to stop my GPS at camp. I set up camp just a mile or two from the trailhead by the river and did most of the trip with a day pack. It was fast, easy going until the leaf litter made following the trail from Rocky Mountain to Balsam Cap tough to follow, which led to some bushwhacking. I found it easier to spot the trail on the way back, but it did seem to disappear periodically. The unmaintained trail from Rocky Mountain down the valley is basically nonexistent. I spent a couple hours of frustrating bushwhacking as the sun set to get down to the river, where there is a fairly open trail on the southern bank of the East Branch Neversink River. However, this trail periodically disappears and often shifts side to side, so it was at times difficult to follow, particularly in the dark. There s one point where the trail is open and easy by the river, but then it terminates when a rocky bluff moves up flush against the river. I m not sure the typical move there, but I just went straight up the bluff and bushwhacked maybe 10ish minutes on top before seeing the trail again below and making my way back down to it. There are a few sections where multiple small rivers criss cross over the trail, and it becomes pretty tough to follow then. I m sure I caught at least a hundred spiders to my face from the bushwhacking. My takeaway was that in the Catskills, a maintained trail is just about as easy as a trail can be, but an unmaintained one is somewhere between frequently lost due to vegetation and blowdowns to nonexistent and a full on bushwhack.

I started at the Wood Valley Campground around 2 PM and dropped off my tent at the spot overlooking a ledge at 2200 ft by 3 PM on the ascent to Wittenberg. I summited Wittenberg by 4:45 and Cornell by 5:15. I made it to the summit of Slide by 6:30, and then I had a choice of completing the Burroughs loop by continuing down in the same direction on easier trail but adding a bunch of length and time to get back to my camp or going back up and over Cornell and Wittenberg to go back to my camp. I chose the latter, which I think saved me a bunch of time. I got back to camp around 9-10 PM. It took maybe 45 minutes the next morning to get back to the trailhead, at which point I drove off to the Giant Ledge TH to do Panther. There were some steep sections with minor 8-20 foot  scrambles  between Wittenberg and Cornell and before Wittenberg, but mostly the trail was pretty nice, even in the dark.

Started from the Giant Ledge TH after doing Witt, Cornell, and Slide the day before. There s a bit of rocky stuff before you join with the main trail and maybe a couple more sections where you go up a substantial amount of rocks, but most of this trail is really easy going. I went past the summit to the viewpoint on the map just to the north, but I m not sure it s worth doing that. It s a bit more open than the little lookout by the Panther summit, but there s a pile of boulders just off the trail a little south of the summit where if you climb up top I think the view is a bit better.

From the TH off of 23, I hiked a tent in to the camp in the space just south of the Elm Ridge Lean To and dropped it off to continue up to the summit. It only took about 40 min to get to that point. The early part of this trail is a very wide MTB trail, and you ll likely pass a few mountain bikers until the Escarpment Trail gets past all the trail intersections. The trail is still very wide and easy all the way to the summit past the MTB portion. There s a USGS marker in the middle of the trail denoting the summit. There are three lookouts around the summit, with my favorite being the expansive view northeast from the lookout to the east of the summit. I spent the night back by the Lean To with lots of acorns falling down and terrifyingly loud owl  Wooo  calls (probably a barred owl). After a short walk out the next morning, I drove over to the Barnum Road and did an out-and-back for Thomas Cole, Black Dome, and Blackhead.
Summited as part of an out-and-back trip up Thomas Cole, Black Dome, and Blackhead. See peakbagger.com

I went from Barnum Road up Thomas Cole, Black Dome, and Blackhead on an out and back trip. The trail starts out very thin next to some private property but opens up by the time you reach the trail register. It s a pleasant walk with a couple steep, scrambly sections up to Caudal Mountain, and from there it s smooth sailing up the ridge to Thomas Cole and Black Dome. There are some views on Camel s Hump between Caudal and TC. The summit of TC is off the main trail. To get there, branch off to the left (north) by the medium-sized boulder, where you ll see a well-defined trail leading into the trees. I initially bushwhacked in from slightly further east as can be seen on the GPS track, but I found the correct trail after reaching the true summit, which isn t really marked. The summit of Black Dome appears to be on the main trail. There s no view up there, but as you descend east there s a great view facing Blackhead. There s a short stretch of scrambling that feels much harder going down than coming up and a somewhat steep incline hiking down to the col, and then it s pretty easy up to Blackhead. Not much of a view on that summit, but to the west of it is a view point facing Black Dome.

This is a trivial walk up with a north facing viewpoint right by the summit and a south facing viewpoint a couple minutes walk to the west of the summit along the ridge and past the remnants of a very short rail bridge.

The best viewpoint near here isn t where this marker is, but not far past it as you move north along the eastern edge of the ridge. Also, I went over to the marker for Broad Mountain along the forest road and past the power lines. There s no view there, but there s an excellent viewpoint of the oxbow bend in the river just past there to the north along an obvious trail. The marker for Broad Mountain is slightly off trail and in the woods.
